<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lepidium latifolium </i>is a non-native, perennial mustard from Eurasia. Stems originate as rosettes in late fall or early spring. As the plants age, they develop erect stems to 2 m tall with little branching. The root system of the plant expands with age, forming a dense colony of stems originating from buds that develop on the roots. The expanding clones merge to form extensive, monospecific stands. Stems die back to the ground after fruiting, leaving semiwoody stems that may persist for several years as a layer of thatch. Plants produce abundant seed crops, but we know little about conditions for germination and seedling establishment in the field (DiTomaso and Healy 2003, Howald 2000, Renz 2000, Zouhar 2004c). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Lepidium latifolium </i>is invading riparian and wetland settings in California. Plants expand rapidly and form extensive, dense patches in both freshwater and brackish water sites in the state. This invasion is magnified in disturbed brackish marshes of the San Francisco Bay estuary, where <i>L. latifolium </i>invades first after disturbance along levees and then spreads into diked and tidal wetlands. Truncation and degradation of the high marsh also occurs through diking, which compresses the habitat into unnaturally steep slopes of disturbed bay mud (Baye 2000).<br/>
<br/>
Other non-native wetland or facultative forb species such as <i>Chenopodium album, Cirsium arvense, Conyza canadensis, Lactuca serriola, Rumex crispus</i>, and <i>Sisymbrium altissimum</i> are common across the state and throughout western North America in similar settings as <i>Lepidium latifolium</i> and can form stands; yet we need more information on their extent and distribution in California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
