    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Lepidium latifolium</i> includes all sections of the state except the Colorado Desert (322C) and Sonoran Desert (322B), and therefore may form stands in additional areas. As a state-listed noxious weed, it is often a target for weed management. Other non-native forbs are common in freshwater to brackish sites across California, including both Desert and Cismontane regions of California.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Ad, Ah, Ak). Stands are common around the edges of salt marshes in San Francisco Bay (Baye et al. 2000) and elsewhere in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad). Stands were mapped directly adjacent to the subsection (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007) are associated commonly with edges of brackish marshes with <i>Atriplex prostrata, Distichlis spicata, </i>and <i>Sonchus oleraceus</i>. Stands at Suisun Marsh (Baye et al. 2000) form monotypic patches in the middle and high brackish marshes with <i>D. spicata</i>. Stands here increased by more than 70% between 1999 and 2006 (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000, VegCAMP 2007b) and increased more in tidal areas than leveed areas between 2012 and 2015 (Boul et al. 2018). Managers at the Cosumnes River Preserve in Sacramento Co. use herbicides to remove <i>L. latifolium </i>(J. Buck, pers. comm. 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh). Stands of this alliance were mapped in Fish Slough (VegCAMP 2014b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac). Stands in Sonoma County are adjacent to salt and brackish marshes (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) have <i>Artemisia douglasiana, Baccharis salicifolia, </i>and emergent <i>Fraxinus velutina </i>and <i>Quercus lobata </i>trees.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). Stands in central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) and in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005) have low cover of <i>Baccharis salicifolia, Sambucus nigra, </i>and <i>Salix gooddingii</i>.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The aggressive invasion of <i>Lepidium latifolium </i>is of particular concern for conservation and recovery of rare or endangered plants in the San Francisco Bay estuary. Stands forming at Suisun Marsh and Southhampton Bay are adjacent to populations of <i>Cirsium hydrophilum </i>(CNPS list 1B.1 plant) and <i>Cordylanthus mollis </i>ssp. <i>mollis </i>and <i>Symphyotrichum lentum </i>(CNPS list 1B.2 plants) (Baye et al. 2000). Concerted eradication measures are occurring in Grizzly Island Wildlife Area. Renz (2000) discussed control strategies for this highly noxious plant. </div>
</div>

    

    

